{"title_page": "Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond, Virginia)", "text_new": "{{coord|37.532108|-77.426031|type:landmark_region:US-VA|display=title}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name             = Poe Museum\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Poe museum800px.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = \n| alt              = \n| map_type         = \n| map_caption      = \n| map_alt          = \n| coordinates      = \n| established      = 1922\n| dissolved        = \n| location         = 1914 E. Main St., <br>[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| type             = Biographical museum\n| collection       = \n| visitors         = \n| director         = Jaime Fawcett\n| president        = Annemarie Beebe\n| curator          = Chris Semtner\n| publictransit    = \n| network          = \n| website          = http://www.poemuseum.org/\n| nrhp = \n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | embed=yes\n  | name = Old Stone House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register\n  | designated_other1_date = October 16, 1973<ref name=register>{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053819/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 127-0100\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n| designated_other2        = Richmond City Historic District\n| designated_other2_name   = Richmond City Historic District\n| designated_other2_abbr   = \n| designated_other2_color  = \n| designated_other2_link   = Richmond,_Virginia#Historic_Districts\n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= \n  | coordinates              = {{coord|37|31|55|N|77|25|35|W|display=inline}}\n| locmapin = \n  | built = 1750\n  | architecture = Colonial\n  | added = November 14, 1973\n  | area = {{convert|1|acre|sigfig=1}}\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum = 73002222\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}<!--oldtitle name, for reference [[File:Poe museum800px.jpg|thumb|right|The Edgar Allan Poe Museum in Richmond, December 2009]]-->\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe Museum''', or the '''Poe Museum''', is a [[museum]] located in the [[Shockoe Bottom]] neighborhood of [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States]], dedicated to American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]]. Though Poe never lived in the building, it serves to commemorate his time living in Richmond. The museum holds one of the world's largest collections of original [[manuscript]]s, letters, first editions, memorabilia and personal belongings. The museum also provides an overview of early 19th century Richmond, where Poe lived and worked. The museum features the life and career of Poe by documenting his accomplishments with pictures, relics, and verse, and focusing on his many years in Richmond.\n\n== Old Stone House ==\nThe Poe Museum is located at the \"'''Old Stone House'''\", built circa 1740<ref name=autogenerated1>Scott, Mary Wingfield, ''Houses of Old Richmond'', The Valentine Museum, Richmond, 1941, pp 7-10</ref><ref>[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/richmond/Antebellumessay.html Richmond: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and cited as the oldest original building in Richmond.<ref name=\"APVA: Old Stone House\">[http://www.apva.org/oldstonehouse/ APVA: Old Stone House] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609214632/http://www.apva.org/oldstonehouse/ |date=2008-06-09 }}</ref> It was built by Jacob Ege,<ref name=autogenerated2>Scott, Mary Wingfield, ''op. cit'' pp 7-10</ref><ref>Ege, Rev. Thompson P, D.D., ''History and Genealogy of the Ege Family in the United States, 1738-1911'', Star Printing Co., Harrisburg, PA, 1911, pp 5-11</ref> who immigrated from [[Germany]] to [[Philadelphia]] in 1738 and came to the James River Settlements and Col. Wm. Byrd's land grant (now known as Richmond) in the company of the family of his fianc\u00e9e, Maria Dorothea Scheerer, whom he later married; the house was a \"Home for the Bride.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>Ege, ''op. cit.'' pp 5-11</ref> (One of Jacob's nephews, [[George Ege]], was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] from [[Berks County, Pennsylvania|Berks County]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>Ege, ''ibid,'' pp 76-78</ref>) [[Dendrochronology]] suggests that additional construction on the house occurred in 1754. Jacob Ege died in 1762.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Samuel Ege, the son of Jacob and a Richmond flour inspector, owned the house in 1782 when it first appeared on a tax register.<ref name=\"APVA: Old Stone House\"/><ref name=\"books.google.de\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=PtC31Ek28o0C&lpg=PA101&ots=aNRdDWT6fA&dq=ege%20family%20richmond&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=ege%20family%20richmond&f=false Scott Bergman, Sandi Bergman, ''Haunted Richmond: The Shadows of Shockoe'', Charleston 2007, p. 102] Google Books</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hH5IAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA18&ots=3TWmq_WtBQ&dq=ege%20family%20richmond&pg=PP7#v=onepage&q=ege%20family%20richmond&f=false Thompson Prettyman Ege: ''History and genealogy of the Ege family in the United States, 1738-1911'', New York, 1911] Google Books</ref>\n\nIn 1824, when the [[Gilbert du Motier, marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]] revisited Richmond, a volunteer company of young Richmonders, the Junior Morgan Riflemen, rode in procession along Lafayette's carriage. One of the riflemen, the then 15-year-old Edgar Allan Poe, stood as honorguard outside the Ege house as Lafayette visited its inhabitants.<ref name=\"books.google.de\"/><ref>Keshia A. Case, Christopher P. Semtner: ''Edgar Allan Poe in Richmond'', Charleston etc., 2009, p. 31 {{ISBN|978-0-7385-6714-3}}</ref><ref>Kenneth Silverman: ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-Ending Remembrance'', New York, 1991, p. 24f. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> The house remained in possession of the Ege family until 1911.\n\n==Museum history==\nAmidst Poe's centennial in 1909, a group of Richmond residents campaigned for the city to better recognize the writer. Citizens asked the city council to erect a statue of Poe on [[Monument Avenue]], but were turned down because he was deemed a disreputable character. The same group went on to found the Poe Museum.<ref>Harry Lee Poe: ''Edgar Allan Poe: An Illustrated Companion to His Tell-Tale Stories''. New York: Metro Books, 2008: 9. {{ISBN|978-1-4351-0469-3}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' called 1909 a banner year for acknowledgement of the importance of Poe, mentioning the Richmond museum.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rothstein|first1=Edward|title=For Poe, This Has Been the Year to Die For|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/01/arts/design/01poe.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 September 2016|date=30 November 2009}}</ref> In 1911, [[Preservation Virginia]] (formerly known as the [[Association for the Preservation of Virginia Antiquities]]) saved the house and opened it in 1922 as the Old Stone House.\n\nThe museum is only blocks away from the sites of Poe's Richmond homes and place of employment, the ''[[Southern Literary Messenger]]''. It is also a few blocks from the grave of his mother [[Eliza Poe]] who was buried in Richmond's [[Church Hill, Richmond, Virginia|Church Hill]] neighborhood, in the graveyard of [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St John's Church]]. Poe never lived in this home. Its completion, originally as the \"Edgar Allan Poe Shrine\", was announced on October 7, 1921:\n<blockquote>This day... at a first expense of about $20,000, completes the Edgar Allan Poe Shrine, and marks the seventy-second anniversary of the death of the poet. If he is aware of mundane affairs he must be pleased to find that, at length, there has been reared to his memory a lasting and appropriate memorial.<ref>Mary E. Phillips: ''Edgar Allan Poe: The Man''. Chicago: The John C. Winston Company, 1926. p. 1524-1525</ref></blockquote>\n\nActor [[Vincent Price]], who had played in numerous film roles based on Poe stories, was a noted fan of the author. He visited the museum in 1975 and had his photo taken with the museum's renowned stuffed raven. In 2014, his daughter [[Victoria Price]] visited the museum, saying that Poe had been such a part of her life that she thought of him as her uncle. In 2016 Victoria Price returned to Richmond as part of a film festival featuring Poe films. The festival, in addition to a ''Poe Goes to the Movies'' ''Unhappy Hour'' with Victoria Price at the Poe Museum, presented films at Richmond's historic [[Byrd Theatre]] and ''An Evening with Victoria Price'' at the Cultural Arts Center in [[Glen Allen, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Curran|first1=Colleen|title=Poe Museum celebrates Edgar Allan Poe with the International Poe Film Festival|url=http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/article_555b25b6-04d3-5f3e-9b4a-d9e665b964a7.html|website=Richmond.com|publisher=Richmond Times-Dispatch|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibits ==\n\nThe Poe Museum's three buildings contain exhibits focusing on different aspects of the author's life and legacy. The parlor of the Old Stone House is used for the display of furniture from the homes in which Edgar Poe and his sister Rosalie Mackenzie Poe lived. Of special interest in this room is a piano that once belonged to Poe's sister.\n\nThe Model Building contains an eighteen-foot-long model of Richmond as Poe would have known it. Also displayed in this gallery are Poe's boyhood bed and furnishings from his boyhood home. The Elizabeth Arnold Poe Memorial Building includes many first and early editions of Poe's works including an 1845 publication of \"[[The Raven]]\" and one of only 12 known existing copies of Poe's first collection ''[[Tamerlane and Other Poems]].''<ref>Lloyd Rose: \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/travel/index/stories/rose05101998.htm Yo, Poe: In Richmond, a museum rises from the dead].\" ''The Washington Post,'' May 10, 1998.</ref> Among the highlights of the collection displayed in this building are Poe's vest, trunk, and walking stick and a lock of his hair. Manuscripts and rare early [[daguerreotype]]s and portraits are also exhibited there. The Exhibits Building is devoted to temporary exhibits related to Poe's place in popular culture. One such exhibit was dedicated to the many theories of [[Death of Edgar Allan Poe|Poe's death]] and another featured illustrations of the poem by artist [[James William Carling]]. Other recent exhibits include \"Poe in Comics\", \"Poe Face to Face: Early Portraits and Daguerreotypes of Edgar Allan Poe\" and \"Ratiocination: Poe the Detective\".<ref>Neimeyer, Mark. \"Poe and popular culture\" as collected in ''The Cambridge Companion to Edgar Allan Poe'', Kevin J. Hayes, editor. Cambridge University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-521-79727-6}} p. 212</ref>\n\nA courtyard area behind the museum includes a garden inspired by Poe's poem \"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#To One in Paradise (1833)|To One in Paradise]].\" This space is also available for weddings.<ref>[http://www.poemuseum.org/about_the_museum/weddings.html Poe Museum homepage - weddings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204033938/http://www.poemuseum.org/about_the_museum/weddings.html |date=2009-12-04 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum]] in Baltimore, Maryland\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in The Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.poemuseum.org/ Edgar Allan Poe Museum] official site\n*[https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/va0571/ Old Stone House, 1916 East Main Street, Richmond, Independent City, VA]: 5 photos, 8 measured drawings, and 5 data pages at [[Historic American Buildings Survey]]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poe, Edgar Allan}}\n[[Category:Museums established in 1922]]\n[[Category:Edgar Allan Poe|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]]\n[[Category:Museums in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Literary museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Colonial architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1750]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|37.532108|-77.426031|type:landmark_region:US-VA|display=title}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name             = Poe Museum\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Poe museum800px.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = \n| alt              = \n| map_type         = \n| map_caption      = \n| map_alt          = \n| coordinates      = \n| established      = 1922\n| dissolved        = \n| location         = 1914 E. Main St., <br>[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| type             = Biographical museum\n| collection       = \n| visitors         = \n| director         = Jaime Fawcett\n| president        = Annemarie Beebe\n| curator          = Chris Semtner\n| publictransit    = \n| network          = \n| website          = http://www.poemuseum.org/\n| nrhp = \n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | embed=yes\n  | name = Old Stone House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register\n  | designated_other1_date = October 16, 1973<ref name=register>{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053819/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 127-0100\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n| designated_other2        = Richmond City Historic District\n| designated_other2_name   = Richmond City Historic District\n| designated_other2_abbr   = \n| designated_other2_color  = \n| designated_other2_link   = Richmond,_Virginia#Historic_Districts\n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= \n  | coordinates              = {{coord|37|31|55|N|77|25|35|W|display=inline}}\n| locmapin = \n  | built = 1750\n  | architecture = Colonial\n  | added = November 14, 1973\n  | area = {{convert|1|acre|sigfig=1}}\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum = 73002222\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}<!--oldtitle name, for reference [[File:Poe museum800px.jpg|thumb|right|The Edgar Allan Poe Museum in Richmond, December 2009]]-->\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe Museum''', or the '''Poe Museum''', is a [[museum]] located in the [[Shockoe Bottom]] neighborhood of [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States]], dedicated to American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]]. Though Poe never lived in the building, it serves to commemorate his time living in Richmond. The museum holds one of the world's largest collections of original [[manuscript]]s, letters, first editions, memorabilia and personal belongings. The museum also provides an overview of early 19th century Richmond, where Poe lived and worked. The museum features the life and career of Poe by documenting his accomplishments with pictures, relics, and verse, and focusing on his many years in Richmond.\n\n== Old Stone House ==\nThe Poe Museum is located at the \"'''Old Stone House'''\", built circa 1740<ref name=autogenerated1>Scott, Mary Wingfield, ''Houses of Old Richmond'', The Valentine Museum, Richmond, 1941, pp 7-10</ref><ref>[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/richmond/Antebellumessay.html Richmond: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and cited as the oldest original building in Richmond.<ref name=\"APVA: Old Stone House\">[http://www.apva.org/oldstonehouse/ APVA: Old Stone House] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609214632/http://www.apva.org/oldstonehouse/ |date=2008-06-09 }}</ref> It was built by Jacob Ege,<ref name=autogenerated2>Scott, Mary Wingfield, ''op. cit'' pp 7-10</ref><ref>Ege, Rev. Thompson P, D.D., ''History and Genealogy of the Ege Family in the United States, 1738-1911'', Star Printing Co., Harrisburg, PA, 1911, pp 5-11</ref> who immigrated from [[Germany]] to [[Philadelphia]] in 1738 and came to the James River Settlements and Col. Wm. Byrd's land grant (now known as Richmond) in the company of the family of his fianc\u00e9e, Maria Dorothea Scheerer, whom he later married; the house was a \"Home for the Bride.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>Ege, ''op. cit.'' pp 5-11</ref> (One of Jacob's nephews, [[George Ege]], was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] from [[Berks County, Pennsylvania|Berks County]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>Ege, ''ibid,'' pp 76-78</ref>) [[Dendrochronology]] suggests that additional construction on the house occurred in 1754. Jacob Ege died in 1762.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Samuel Ege, the son of Jacob and a Richmond flour inspector, owned the house in 1782 when it first appeared on a tax register.<ref name=\"APVA: Old Stone House\"/><ref name=\"books.google.de\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=PtC31Ek28o0C&lpg=PA101&ots=aNRdDWT6fA&dq=ege%20family%20richmond&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=ege%20family%20richmond&f=false Scott Bergman, Sandi Bergman, ''Haunted Richmond: The Shadows of Shockoe'', Charleston 2007, p. 102] Google Books</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hH5IAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA18&ots=3TWmq_WtBQ&dq=ege%20family%20richmond&pg=PP7#v=onepage&q=ege%20family%20richmond&f=false Thompson Prettyman Ege: ''History and genealogy of the Ege family in the United States, 1738-1911'', New York, 1911] Google Books</ref> \n\nIn 1824, when the [[Gilbert du Motier, marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]] revisited Richmond, a volunteer company of young Richmonders, the Junior Morgan Riflemen, rode in procession along Lafayette's carriage. One of the riflemen, the then 15-year-old Edgar Allan Poe, stood as honorguard outside the Ege house as Lafayette visited its inhabitants.<ref name=\"books.google.de\"/><ref>Keshia A. Case, Christopher P. Semtner: ''Edgar Allan Poe in Richmond'', Charleston etc., 2009, p. 31 {{ISBN|978-0-7385-6714-3}}</ref><ref>Kenneth Silverman: ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-Ending Remembrance'', New York, 1991, p. 24f. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> The house remained in possession of the Ege family until 1911.\n\n==Museum history==\nAmidst Poe's centennial in 1909, a group of Richmond residents campaigned for the city to better recognize the writer. Citizens asked the city council to erect a statue of Poe on [[Monument Avenue]], but were turned down because he was deemed a disreputable character. The same group went on to found the Poe Museum.<ref>Harry Lee Poe: ''Edgar Allan Poe: An Illustrated Companion to His Tell-Tale Stories''. New York: Metro Books, 2008: 9. {{ISBN|978-1-4351-0469-3}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' called 1909 a banner year for acknowledgement of the importance of Poe, mentioning the Richmond museum.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rothstein|first1=Edward|title=For Poe, This Has Been the Year to Die For|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/01/arts/design/01poe.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 September 2016|date=30 November 2009}}</ref> In 1911, [[Preservation Virginia]] (formerly known as the [[Association for the Preservation of Virginia Antiquities]]) saved the house and opened it in 1922 as the Old Stone House.\n\nThe museum is only blocks away from the sites of Poe's Richmond homes and place of employment, the ''[[Southern Literary Messenger]]''. It is also a few blocks from the grave of his mother [[Eliza Poe]] who was buried in Richmond's [[Church Hill, Richmond, Virginia|Church Hill]] neighborhood, in the graveyard of [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St John's Church]]. Poe never lived in this home. Its completion, originally as the \"Edgar Allan Poe Shrine\", was announced on October 7, 1921:\n<blockquote>This day... at a first expense of about $20,000, completes the Edgar Allan Poe Shrine, and marks the seventy-second anniversary of the death of the poet. If he is aware of mundane affairs he must be pleased to find that, at length, there has been reared to his memory a lasting and appropriate memorial.<ref>Mary E. Phillips: ''Edgar Allan Poe: The Man''. Chicago: The John C. Winston Company, 1926. p. 1524-1525</ref></blockquote>\n\nActor [[Vincent Price]], who had played in numerous film roles based on Poe stories, was a noted fan of the author. He visited the museum in 1975 and had his photo taken with the museum's renowned stuffed raven. In 2014, his daughter [[Victoria Price]] visited the museum, saying that Poe had been such a part of her life that she thought of him as her uncle. In 2016 Victoria Price returned to Richmond as part of a film festival featuring Poe films. The festival, in addition to a ''Poe Goes to the Movies'' ''Unhappy Hour'' with Victoria Price at the Poe Museum, presented films at Richmond's historic [[Byrd Theatre]] and ''An Evening with Victoria Price'' at the Cultural Arts Center in [[Glen Allen, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Curran|first1=Colleen|title=Poe Museum celebrates Edgar Allan Poe with the International Poe Film Festival|url=http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/article_555b25b6-04d3-5f3e-9b4a-d9e665b964a7.html|website=Richmond.com|publisher=Richmond Times-Dispatch|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibits ==\n\nThe Poe Museum's three buildings contain exhibits focusing on different aspects of the author's life and legacy. The parlor of the Old Stone House is used for the display of furniture from the homes in which Edgar Poe and his sister Rosalie Mackenzie Poe lived. Of special interest in this room is a piano that once belonged to Poe's sister.\n\nThe Model Building contains an eighteen-foot-long model of Richmond as Poe would have known it. Also displayed in this gallery are Poe's boyhood bed and furnishings from his boyhood home. The Elizabeth Arnold Poe Memorial Building includes many first and early editions of Poe's works including an 1845 publication of \"[[The Raven]]\" and one of only 12 known existing copies of Poe's first collection ''[[Tamerlane and Other Poems]].''<ref>Lloyd Rose: \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/travel/index/stories/rose05101998.htm Yo, Poe: In Richmond, a museum rises from the dead].\" ''The Washington Post,'' May 10, 1998.</ref> Among the highlights of the collection displayed in this building are Poe's vest, trunk, and walking stick and a lock of his hair. Manuscripts and rare early [[daguerreotype]]s and portraits are also exhibited there. The Exhibits Building is devoted to temporary exhibits related to Poe's place in popular culture. One such exhibit was dedicated to the many theories of [[Death of Edgar Allan Poe|Poe's death]] and another featured illustrations of the poem by artist [[James William Carling]]. Other recent exhibits include \"Poe in Comics\", \"Poe Face to Face: Early Portraits and Daguerreotypes of Edgar Allan Poe\" and \"Ratiocination: Poe the Detective\".<ref>Neimeyer, Mark. \"Poe and popular culture\" as collected in ''The Cambridge Companion to Edgar Allan Poe'', Kevin J. Hayes, editor. Cambridge University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-521-79727-6}} p. 212</ref>\n\nA courtyard area behind the museum includes a garden inspired by Poe's poem \"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#To One in Paradise (1833)|To One in Paradise]].\" This space is also available for weddings.<ref>[http://www.poemuseum.org/about_the_museum/weddings.html Poe Museum homepage - weddings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204033938/http://www.poemuseum.org/about_the_museum/weddings.html |date=2009-12-04 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum]] in Baltimore, Maryland\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in The Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.poemuseum.org/ Edgar Allan Poe Museum] official site\n*[https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/va0571/ Old Stone House, 1916 East Main Street, Richmond, Independent City, VA]: 5 photos, 8 measured drawings, and 5 data pages at [[Historic American Buildings Survey]]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poe, Edgar Allan}}\n[[Category:Museums established in 1922]]\n[[Category:Edgar Allan Poe|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]]\n[[Category:Museums in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Literary museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Colonial architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1750]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgar_Allan_Poe_Museum_(Richmond,_Virginia)"}
{"title_page": "Shiba Shanu", "text_new": "{{short description|Bangladeshi actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Shiba Shanu\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| native_name   = \u09b6\u09bf\u09ac\u09be \u09b6\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| birth_name    = Chowdhury Mazhar Ali\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1974|08|07}}\n| birth_place   = [[Dhaka Division|Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| death_date   = \n| nationality   = Bangladeshi\n| yearsactive   = 1998\u2013present\n| occupation    = Actor, \n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Chowdhury Mazhar Ali''' (born: 7 August 1974; Popularly known as '''Shiba Shanu''') is a Bangladeshi film actor. He is mostly known for his villain role in the Bengali film. In 1998, He started his film career with the film Matrivumi.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagonews24.com/entertainment/news/471338|title=\u0985\u09ad\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09a4\u09be \u09b6\u09bf\u09ac\u09be \u09b8\u09be\u09a8\u09c1 \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09b0\u09c7|website=jagonews24.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntvbd.com/bangladesh/230365/%E0%A6%85%E0%A6%AD%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B9-%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%97%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%87|title=\u0985\u09ad\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09a4\u09be \u09b6\u09bf\u09ac\u09be \u09b6\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b8\u09b9 \u099a\u09be\u09b0\u099c\u09a8 \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09b0\u09c7|date=December 25, 2018|website=NTV Online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bd-pratidin.com/entertainment-news/2017/10/15/272177|title=\u0996\u09b2\u09a8\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u0995 \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u099f\u09c7 \u09a2\u09be\u0995\u09be\u0987 \u099a\u09b2\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0 &#124; \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u09a6\u0