{"title_page": "Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Edgar Allan Poe House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = PoeHouse-Baltimore.jpg\n| caption = Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| location = [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|39|17|28.65|N|76|37|59.30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA\n| area =\n| built = 1830\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |title=Poe, Edgar Allan, House |accessdate=2009-03-30 |work=National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher=National Park Service |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308085504/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |archive-date=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| added = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 71001043\n}}\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum''', located at 203 North Amity St. in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], is the former home of American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 1830s. The small unassuming structure, which was opened as a [[writer's house museum]] in 1949, is a typical [[Terraced house|row home]]. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1972.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/>\n\nDue to a loss of funding by the city of Baltimore, the Museum closed to the public in October 2012. [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], the Museum's new governing body, reopened the Museum to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-10-05/entertainment/bs-hs-poe-house-20131005_1_poe-baltimore-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore-office|title=Edgar Allan Poe's house reopened to the public|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe brick home, then numbered 3 Amity St.,<ref name=Silverman96>Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> and now numbered 203 North Amity Street, is assumed to have been built in 1830 and rented by Poe's aunt Maria Clemm in 1832. Clemm was joined in the home by her ailing mother, Elizabeth Cairnes Poe, and her daughter [[Virginia Eliza Clemm Poe|Virginia Clemm]]. Edgar Allan Poe moved in with the family in 1833<ref name=Silverman96/> around the age of 23, after leaving [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Virginia was 10 years old at the time; Poe would marry her three years later, though their only public ceremony was in 1836. Poe lived in the house from about 1833 to 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html|title=Fiscal Woe Haunting Baltimore Poe House|date=8 August 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe house was rented using [[pension]] money that Elizabeth collected thanks to her husband, David Poe Sr., who was a veteran of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. The home is small and Poe's room on the top floor has a ceiling with a sharp pitch which is six feet high at its tallest point.<ref>Haas, Irvin. ''Historic Homes of American Authors''. Washington, DC: The Preservation Press, 1991. {{ISBN|0-89133-180-8}}. p. 78</ref>\n\nIn the 1930s, homes in the area, including Poe's, were set for demolition to make room for the \"Poe Homes\" [[public housing]] project.  The house was saved by the efforts of the [http://www.eapoe.org Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore], which made arrangements with the city of Baltimore and opened the home as [http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm The Baltimore Poe House] in 1949. \nFormer displays in the Museum included a lock of Poe's hair, a small piece of Poe's coffin, some original china that once belonged to John Allan (Poe's guardian after [[Eliza Poe]]'s death), and a large reproduction of the portrait of Virginia Clemm painted after her death as well as many other Poe-related images. An original 1849 [[obituary]] by Rufus Griswold in the October 24, 1849 edition of the ''Philadelphia Dollar Newspaper'' is also on display along with a reprint of Poe's original announcement for the creation of a new literary magazine to be called ''[[The Stylus]]'' &mdash; an endeavor that never came to fruition.\n\nThe Museum hosted a number of Poe events throughout the year. It claimed, for example, the largest Poe birthday celebration in the world held every January at the [[Westminster Hall and Burying Ground]], where Poe was buried following his death in October 1849. In 2009, the curator, Jeff Jerome, planned the biggest event of the Poe Bicentennial at Westminster Hall. He held a third funeral for Poe. Over 1,200 people attended two services. The event received national and international media attention and acclaim.\n\nIn 1979 during the house renovations, workers lifted the floorboards and found skeletal remains, reminiscent of Poe's story \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]].\" These were found to be animal bones discarded into what is known as a \"trash pit\" or [[midden]] beneath the home.<ref>Gentile, Sal. \"[http://www.wboc.com/story/6844463/edgar-allan-poe-museum-staff-make-disturbing-find Edgar Allan Poe Museum staff make disturbing find],\" Associated Press. July 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, City of Baltimore officials reduced the Museum's subsidy, a decision that ultimately led to its closure in 2012. After the City cut off its $85,000 in annual support in 2011, the Museum was operating on reserve funds to the amount of $380,000 in the Poe House Fundraising account.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html |work=The New York Times |first=Kate |last=Taylor |title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing |date=August 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEfforts to secure the Museum's future came from such diverse places as: the non-profit project [http://penniesforpoe.com/ Pennies For Poe: Save the Poe House in Baltimore],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-10-06/entertainment/bs-ae-poe-fundraising-20111006_1_poe-fans-edgar-allan-poe-house-jeff-jerome|title=Plight of Baltimore's Poe House attracts worldwide attention|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> the New York City based non-profit theatre company [http://www.bedlamensemble.org/press.php Bedlam Ensemble's] staging of ''The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitaljournal.com/article/313315|title='The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe' to benefit Poe House and Museum (Includes interview)|work=digitaljournal.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> and the 2012 film [[The Raven (2012 film)|''The Raven'']].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/08/could-the-poe-movie-save-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore.html |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Carolyn |last=Kellogg |title=Could the Poe movie save Edgar Allan Poe's Baltimore house? |date=August 8, 2011}} [Author refers to the upcoming 2012 film ''The Raven'']</ref>\n\nJeff Jerome, the Museum's [[curator]] for more than three decades, was laid off in 2012. According to the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore, the Museum was closed on September 28, 2012 with no advance public notice, with plans to reorganize and reopen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm |title=Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum |url-status=live |accessdate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==Poe Baltimore==\nIn 2013, a new non-profit organization, [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], was established to serve as the Museum's new governing body and operate the Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum.\n\nPoe Baltimore's [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/mission-statement/ Mission Statement] includes that the organization \"...was created to fund, maintain and interpret The Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum, and to celebrate the legacy of one of Baltimore\u2019s most famous residents.  We are dedicated to maintaining the museum as a vibrant experience for the thousands of visitors who come from around the world each year, and as part of a broader mission of city-wide events and educational opportunities...\"\n\n[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] reopened the [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/museum/ Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum] to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\"/> [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] is also working in conjunction with the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore.\n\n==Description==\nThe Poe House is a {{frac|2|1|2}} story two-bay brick structure with a gabled metal roof. The front door is on the left side of the west elevation, at the top of a wood stoop. The house is flanked on the north by a contiguous building; the south elevation is windowless. A single gabled [[dormer]] is centered in the west roof. To the rear a two-story ell projects from the south side of the main block. Its shed roof slopes to the north.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=71001043}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination: Edgar Allan Poe House|last=Mendinghall|first=Joseph S.|author2=Preston, Edmund|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> The house sits on the western edge of an active low-income housing project in the west Baltimore neighborhood of [[Poppleton, Baltimore|Poppleton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html?hp | work=The New York Times | first=Kate | last=Taylor | title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing | date=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929234725/http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe house is entered through the front living room, with a dining room to the rear and two steps down. From the dining room narrow stairs lead to the basement and the second floor. Two bedrooms occupy the second floor, and stairs lead to a small attic or garret, which may have been occupied by Poe. The house retains the majority of its original woodwork.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\"/>\n\n==Works penned in this house==\nThough it cannot be fully proven, the Poe Society alleges that the following works were created while Poe was staying in this house:\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Stories'''\n\n*''[[MS. Found in a Bottle]]''\n*''Lionizing: A Tale''\n*''Shadow-A Parable''\n*''[[Berenice (short story)|Berenice]]''\n*''[[Morella (short story)|Morella]]''\n*''[[King Pest|King Pest the First. A Tale containing an Allegory]]''\n*''[[The Unparalleled Adventure of One Hans Pfaall]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Poems'''\n\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Hymn (1835)|Latin Hymn]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Enigma(1833)|Enigma]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Serenade (1833)|Serenade]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#The Coliseum (1833)|The Coliseum]]\"\n|}\n\n==Poe House in popular culture==\nIn the opening scene of episode 2, season 3 \"[[All Due Respect (The Wire)|All Due Respect]],\" of the [[HBO]] series ''[[The Wire]]'', two low-level members of the [[Barksdale Organization|Barksdale Gang]] recall how one was once approached by a white tourist asking him if he knew the location of the \"Poe House\". Misunderstanding, he replies \"Look around, take your pick!\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113132949/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''The Wire'' chronicles the activities of the fictional Barksdale Organization based in west Baltimore, where the Poe House is located.\n\nIn season 3 of the Telltale Games video game version of ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', one house in the Prescott camp is a visual homage to the Poe House.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond)|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in [[Philadelphia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in the Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum}}\n*[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore]\n*[http://www.eapoe.org The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/baltimore/index.htm  Baltimore, Maryland, a National Park Service ''Discover Our Shared Heritage'' Travel Itinerary]\n*[http://explore.baltimoreheritage.org/items/show/77?tour=12&index=12#.UlcUlijcGgw Explore Baltimore Heritage. Edgar Allan Poe House. By Ryan Artes, University of Baltimore]\n*[http://citylitproject.org/index.cfm?page=news&newsid=138 Poe House: Landmark Returns with a \"Poe\"-pen House. Oct. 3, 2013]\n*{{MHT url|id=79|title=Edgar Allan Poe House. National Register Listings in Maryland}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=poe+house,+Baltimore,+Maryland&sll=39.288459,-76.604211&sspn=0.007673,0.014763&ie=UTF8&ll=39.291299,-76.633201&spn=0,359.985237&z=16&layer=c&cbll=39.291379,-76.633209&panoid=vbq2Zy8XHGPZRZZi_VFDHQ&cbp=12,82.29920761890918,,0,-3.360449030098446  Poe House on Google Street View]\n\n{{Edgar Allan Poe|state=expanded}}\n{{Maryland museums|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Maryland}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poe, Edgar Allan, House And Museum}}\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Edgar Allan Poe]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1830]]\n[[Category:Houses in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Literary museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Museums in Baltimore]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Poppleton, Baltimore]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Homes of American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Edgar Allan Poe House\n| nrhp_type = nhl\n| image = PoeHouse-Baltimore.jpg\n| caption = Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| location = [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|39|17|28.65|N|76|37|59.30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA\n| area =\n| built = 1830\n| architect =\n| architecture =\n| designated_nrhp_type = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |title=Poe, Edgar Allan, House |accessdate=2009-03-30 |work=National Historic Landmark summary listing |publisher=National Park Service |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308085504/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1182&ResourceType=Building |archive-date=2009-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| added = November 11, 1972<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| refnum = 71001043\n}}\n\nThe '''Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum''', located at 203 North Amity St. in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], is the former home of American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]] in the 1830s. The small unassuming structure, which was opened as a [[writer's house museum]] in 1949, is a typical [[Terraced house|row home]]. It was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1972.<ref name=\"nhlsum\"/>\n\nDue to a loss of funding by the city of Baltimore, the Museum closed to the public in October 2012. [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], the Museum's new governing body, reopened the Museum to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-10-05/entertainment/bs-hs-poe-house-20131005_1_poe-baltimore-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore-office|title=Edgar Allan Poe's house reopened to the public|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe brick home, then numbered 3 Amity St.,<ref name=Silverman96>Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. p. 96. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}</ref> and now numbered 203 North Amity Street, is assumed to have been built in 1830 and rented by Poe's aunt Maria Clemm in 1832. Clemm was joined in the home by her ailing mother, Elizabeth Cairnes Poe, and her daughter [[Virginia Eliza Clemm Poe|Virginia Clemm]]. Edgar Allan Poe moved in with the family in 1833<ref name=Silverman96/> around the age of 23, after leaving [[United States Military Academy|West Point]]. Virginia was 10 years old at the time; Poe would marry her three years later, though their only public ceremony was in 1836. Poe lived in the house from about 1833 to 1835.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html|title=Fiscal Woe Haunting Baltimore Poe House|date=8 August 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe house was rented using [[pension]] money that Elizabeth collected thanks to her husband, David Poe Sr., who was a veteran of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. The home is small and Poe's room on the top floor has a ceiling with a sharp pitch which is six feet high at its tallest point.<ref>Haas, Irvin. ''Historic Homes of American Authors''. Washington, DC: The Preservation Press, 1991. {{ISBN|0-89133-180-8}}. p. 78</ref>\n\nIn the 1930s, homes in the area, including Poe's, were set for demolition to make room for the \"Poe Homes\" [[public housing]] project.  The house was saved by the efforts of the [http://www.eapoe.org Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore], which made arrangements with the city of Baltimore and opened the home as [http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm The Baltimore Poe House] in 1949. \nFormer displays in the Museum included a lock of Poe's hair, a small piece of Poe's coffin, some original china that once belonged to John Allan (Poe's guardian after [[Eliza Poe]]'s death), and a large reproduction of the portrait of Virginia Clemm painted after her death as well as many other Poe-related images. An original 1849 [[obituary]] by Rufus Griswold in the October 24, 1849 edition of the ''Philadelphia Dollar Newspaper'' is also on display along with a reprint of Poe's original announcement for the creation of a new literary magazine to be called ''[[The Stylus]]'' &mdash; an endeavor that never came to fruition.\n\nThe Museum hosted a number of Poe events throughout the year. It claimed, for example, the largest Poe birthday celebration in the world held every January at the [[Westminster Hall and Burying Ground]], where Poe was buried following his death in October 1849. In 2009, the curator, Jeff Jerome, planned the biggest event of the Poe Bicentennial at Westminster Hall. He held a third funeral for Poe. Over 1,200 people attended two services. The event received national and international media attention and acclaim.\n\nIn 1979 during the house renovations, workers lifted the floorboards and found skeletal remains, reminiscent of Poe's story \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]].\" These were found to be animal bones discarded into what is known as a \"trash pit\" or [[midden]] beneath the home.<ref>Gentile, Sal. \"[http://www.wboc.com/story/6844463/edgar-allan-poe-museum-staff-make-disturbing-find Edgar Allan Poe Museum staff make disturbing find],\" Associated Press. July 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, City of Baltimore officials reduced the Museum's subsidy, a decision that ultimately led to its closure in 2012. After the City cut off its $85,000 in annual support in 2011, the Museum was operating on reserve funds to the amount of $380,000 in the Poe House Fundraising account.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html |work=The New York Times |first=Kate |last=Taylor |title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing |date=August 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEfforts to secure the Museum's future came from such diverse places as: the non-profit project [http://penniesforpoe.com/ Pennies For Poe: Save the Poe House in Baltimore],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-10-06/entertainment/bs-ae-poe-fundraising-20111006_1_poe-fans-edgar-allan-poe-house-jeff-jerome|title=Plight of Baltimore's Poe House attracts worldwide attention|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> the New York City based non-profit theatre company [http://www.bedlamensemble.org/press.php Bedlam Ensemble's] staging of ''The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitaljournal.com/article/313315|title='The Delirium of Edgar Allan Poe' to benefit Poe House and Museum (Includes interview)|work=digitaljournal.com|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> and the 2012 film [[The Raven (2012 film)|''The Raven'']].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/08/could-the-poe-movie-save-edgar-allan-poe-house-baltimore.html |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Carolyn |last=Kellogg |title=Could the Poe movie save Edgar Allan Poe's Baltimore house? |date=August 8, 2011}} [Author refers to the upcoming 2012 film ''The Raven'']</ref>\n\nJeff Jerome, the Museum's [[curator]] for more than three decades, was laid off in 2012. According to the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore, the Museum was closed on September 28, 2012 with no advance public notice, with plans to reorganize and reopen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eapoe.org/balt/poehse.htm |title=Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum |url-status=live |accessdate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==Poe Baltimore==\nIn 2013, a new non-profit organization, [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore], was established to serve as the Museum's new governing body and operate the Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum.\n\nPoe Baltimore's [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/mission-statement/ Mission Statement] includes that the organization \"...was created to fund, maintain and interpret The Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum, and to celebrate the legacy of one of Baltimore\u2019s most famous residents.  We are dedicated to maintaining the museum as a vibrant experience for the thousands of visitors who come from around the world each year, and as part of a broader mission of city-wide events and educational opportunities...\"\n\n[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] reopened the [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/museum/ Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum] to the public on October 5, 2013.<ref name=\"articles.baltimoresun.com\"/> [http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore] is also working in conjunction with the Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore.\n\n==Description==\nThe Poe House is a {{frac|2|1|2}} story two-bay brick structure with a gabled metal roof. The front door is on the left side of the west elevation, at the top of a wood stoop. The house is flanked on the north by a contiguous building; the south elevation is windowless. A single gabled [[dormer]] is centered in the west roof. To the rear a two-story ell projects from the south side of the main block. Its shed roof slopes to the north.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=71001043}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination: Edgar Allan Poe House|last=Mendinghall|first=Joseph S.|author2=Preston, Edmund|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> The house sits on the western edge of an active low-income housing project in the west Baltimore neighborhood of [[Poppleton, Baltimore|Poppleton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/08/arts/edgar-allan-poe-house-in-baltimore-faces-closing.html?hp | work=The New York Times | first=Kate | last=Taylor | title=Edgar Allan Poe House in Baltimore Faces Closing | date=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929234725/http://www.urbanitebaltimore.com/baltimore/picking-poppleton/Content?oid=1245686 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe house is entered through the front living room, with a dining room to the rear and two steps down. From the dining room narrow stairs lead to the basement and the second floor. Two bedrooms occupy the second floor, and stairs lead to a small attic or garret, which may have been occupied by Poe. The house retains the majority of its original woodwork.<ref name=\"nrhpinv1\"/>\n\n==Works penned in this house==\nThough it cannot be fully proven, the Poe Society alleges that the following works were created while Poe was staying in this house:\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Stories'''\n\n*''[[MS. Found in a Bottle]]''\n*''Lionizing: A Tale''\n*''Shadow-A Parable''\n*''[[Berenice (short story)|Berenice]]''\n*''[[Morella (short story)|Morella]]''\n*''[[King Pest|King Pest the First. A Tale containing an Allegory]]''\n*''[[The Unparalleled Adventure of One Hans Pfaall]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n'''Poems'''\n\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Hymn (1835)|Latin Hymn]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Enigma(1833)|Enigma]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#Serenade (1833)|Serenade]]\"\n*\"[[Poems by Edgar Allan Poe#The Coliseum (1833)|The Coliseum]]\"\n|}\n\n==Poe House in popular culture==\nIn the opening scene of episode 2, season 3 \"[[All Due Respect (The Wire)|All Due Respect]],\" of the [[HBO]] series ''[[The Wire]]'', two low-level members of the [[Barksdale Organization|Barksdale Gang]] recall how one was once approached by a white tourist asking him if he knew the location of the \"Poe House\". Misunderstanding, he replies \"Look around, take your pick!\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113132949/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the-wire-1/all-due-respect-1/ |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''The Wire'' chronicles the activities of the fictional Barksdale Organization based in west Baltimore, where the Poe House is located.\n\nIn season 3 of the Telltale Games video game version of ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', one house in the Prescott camp is a visual homage to the Poe House.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond)|Edgar Allan Poe Museum]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe National Historic Site]] in [[Philadelphia]]\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] in the Bronx, New York\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Edgar Allan Poe House and Museum}}\n*[http://www.poeinbaltimore.org/ Poe Baltimore]\n*[http://www.eapoe.org The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/baltimore/index.htm  Baltimore, Maryland, a National Park Service ''Discover Our Shared Heritage'' Travel Itinerary]\n*[http://explore.baltimoreheritage.org/items/show/77?tour=12&index=12#.UlcUlijcGgw Explore Baltimore Heritage. Edgar Allan Poe House. By Ryan Artes, University of Baltimore]\n*[http://citylitproject.org/index.cfm?page=news&newsid=138 Poe House: Landmark Returns with a \"Poe\"-pen House. Oct. 3, 2013]\n*{{MHT url|id=79|title=Edgar Allan Poe House. National Register Listings in Maryland}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=poe+house,+Baltimore,+Maryland&sll=39.288459,-76.604211&s